<DIV1 TYPE="note to the reader">
<HEAD>Adverti&s;ement.</HEAD>
<P>AFTER repeated inquiry, the author could never obtain a &s;ight either of the whole <HI>Ro&s;arie</HI> of the Virgin Mary, or of the whole <HI>Mary-P&s;alter.</HI> Tho&s;e parts of them, which are produced in the foregoing di&s;cour&s;e, were &s;elected from among others of the &s;ame tenor, and tran&s;lated by him from the Latin, as he found it cited by authors of reputation; particularly Doctor Henry More. For other citations he is wholly accountable him&s;elf.&mdash;Many other prayers to the &s;aints, even in the early ages of the church, may be &s;een in Sir I. Newton's <HI>Ob&s;ervations on Daniel,</HI> &amp;c. Part I. ch. 14. And among them a pretty remarkable prayer of Gregory Nazianzen to St. Athana&s;ius; the latter of whom, as Sir I&s;aac ob&s;erves, <Q>even from his youth, looked upon the dead &s;aints as mediators of our prayers,</Q> &amp;c.</P>
